{
  "category": "Uncategorized",
  "description": "Add Microsoft 365 Exchange Email Ingestion via Power Automate\n\nImplement end-to-end support for processing incoming emails from Microsoft 365 Exchange using Power Automate webhooks, including backend ingestion, multi-tenant data storage, and an admin-facing setup guide.\n\nRequirements:\n\nWebhook Endpoint\n- Create a new POST webhook endpoint (e.g., /webhooks/email/microsoft365) that receives email payloads triggered by Power Automate when a new email arrives in Exchange\n- Authenticate incoming requests (e.g., via a shared secret or API key header) to prevent unauthorized submissions\n- Parse and validate the incoming payload, extracting key fields: sender address, recipient(s), subject, body (plain text and HTML), timestamp, attachments metadata, and any relevant message IDs\n- Return appropriate HTTP responses (200 on success, 400 on validation failure, 401 on auth failure) so Power Automate can detect and retry on errors\n\nDatabase\n- Design and create a new emails table to store ingested email records with columns for: tenant ID, message ID (for deduplication), sender, recipients, subject, body content, received timestamp, raw payload, and created/updated timestamps\n- Add a unique constraint on tenant ID + message ID to prevent duplicate ingestion\n- Ensure all queries are scoped by tenant ID to enforce multi-tenant data isolation\n\nMulti-Tenant Support\n- Resolve the tenant from the incoming webhook request (e.g., via a tenant-specific API key, a URL path parameter such as /webhooks/email/microsoft365/:tenantId, or a JWT claim)\n- Ensure no cross-tenant data leakage at the query, storage, and response layer\n\nAdmin Integrations Page\n- Create a new admin page at /admin/integrations\n- Include a clearly titled \"Microsoft 365 / Exchange Email\" section with step-by-step instructions for setting up a Power Automate flow, covering:\n  - Trigger: \"When a new email arrives (V3)\" in Exchange\n  - Action: HTTP POST to the tenant's unique webhook URL\n  - Required headers (Content-Type, auth key)\n  - A mapping guide showing which Power Automate dynamic fields (e.g., From, Subject, Body) map to which webhook payload fields\n  - How to retrieve the tenant's API key or webhook URL from within the admin UI\n- Display the tenant-specific webhook URL prominently so it can be copied directly into Power Automate\n\nEdge Cases to Consider\n- Handle duplicate deliveries gracefully using message ID deduplication\n- Accommodate emails with missing or null optional fields (e.g., no subject, no plain-text body)\n- Handle large email bodies without exceeding payload or database column size limits\n- Validate that the tenant exists and is active before persisting any data\n- Log ingestion failures with enough context for debugging without storing sensitive content\n\nPrerequisites\n- Existing multi-tenant architecture and tenant resolution mechanism in place\n- Admin authentication and role-based access controlling the /admin/integrations route",
  "title": "Implement Microsoft 365 Exchange Email Ingestion",
